results.name: Decimal expansion of Pi^Pi^Pi^Pi.
comment: The offset equals the floor(Pi^Pi^Pi*Log_10(Pi))+1. - _Robert G. Wilson v_, Mar 13 2014
Whether this number is an integer or not is an open question. It is also an open question whether Pi^Pi^Pi^...^Pi^Pi n times is an integer for any natural n > 4. - _Eliora Ben-Gurion_, Nov 17 2019
mathematica: nbrdgt = 105; f[base_, exp_] := RealDigits[ 10^FractionalPart[ N[exp*Log10[base], nbrdgt + Floor[Log10[exp]] + 2]], 10, nbrdgt][[1]]; f[Pi, Pi^Pi^Pi] (* _Robert G. Wilson v_, Mar 13 2014 *)
program: (PARI) LP(a,b)=[10^frac(a=log(a)/log(10)*b),a\1] /* returns [m,e] such that a^b = m*10^e */
results.author: _M. F. Hasler_, Dec 26 2011
